Modelling the impact of passive case detection


Sebastian Funk & Francesco Checchi
28 March, 2017
Warwick University

Passive case detection

  • Element of most HAT control programmes
  • Coverage depends on
    • recognition of cases at community level
    • presentation or referral to treatment centre
  • Potential barriers
    • cultural factors
    • poverty & transport infrastructure

Potential impact of passive case detection

  • Averting severe illness & death
  • Reduction in transmission

Aim of this study

Estimate coverage and epidemiological impact of passive case detection

Conclusions

  • Heterogeneity in incidence
  • Reported burden an underestimate
  • Impact of greater passive case detection

Future research questions

  • What do we see in other foci?
  • How do we improve passive case detection?
  • What do the results mean for (pre-/post-) elimination?
